-- BHP, CSR, Elders, Santos, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-07-04T22:52:54Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-04/bhp-rio-csr-elders-qantas-santos-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in  Australia . This preview
includes news announced after markets closed July 2. All prices
are from that day’s close unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index futures contract due in September
dropped 0.7 percent to 4,213 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The Bank
of New York Australia ADR Index rose 0.5 percent. The S&P/ASX
200 Index was little changed at 4,238.70.  
 Mining shares: Copper futures for September delivery added
1.4 percent to $2.916 a pound on the Comex in New York.  
 BHP Billiton (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
was little changed at A$37.09 in Sydney. Its American depositary
receipts climbed 0.5 percent in New York trading.  
 Rio Tinto Group (RIO AU), the world’s third-largest mining
company, gained 0.3 percent to A$65.30 in Sydney.  
   Oil companies : Oil dropped for a fifth day today. Crude oil
for August delivery traded at $72.28 a barrel, up 14 cents, in
electronic trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange at 8:11
a.m. Sydney time.  
   Woodside Petroleum Ltd . (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, dropped 2.5 percent to A$41.  
   Santos Ltd . (STO AU) declined 1.1 percent to A$12.22.
Santos may consider selling some of its offshore Western
Australian assets for as much as A$1 billion, the Australian
Financial Review reported in its Street Talk column, without
saying where it got the information.  
       CSR Ltd . (CSR AU): Australia’s second-largest building-
products maker received a formal offer from Bright Food Group Co.
Ltd. for its sugar unit Sucrogen, the Australian Financial
Review reported, citing sources it said were close to the deal.
CSR shares climbed 1.5 percent to A$1.695.  
   Elders Ltd . (ELD AU): The world’s largest wool broker
says growing conditions across Australia are “robust” and the
company’s horticulture unit is doing well. Elders shares slumped
3.8 percent to 38 Australian cents.  
        IOOF Holdings Ltd . (IFL AU): The fund manager was rated
“buy” in new coverage at UBS AG by equity analyst Lachlan Parker. IOOF shares advanced 3.8 percent to A$6.06.  
   Qantas Airways Ltd . (QAN AU): Australia’s largest carrier
said that Vietnam had concluded a probe into its Jetstar Pacific
affiliate. Two executives who had been prevented from leaving
Vietnam have now returned to Australia, Qantas spokeswoman
Olivia Wirth said by phone. Qantas rose 1.4 percent to A$2.22.  
